The history of communism in Colombia goes back The history of communism in Colombia goes back over a century, with the first seeds of left-wing political thought being sown in the late 19th century. This was followed by the formation of the Communist Party of Colombia in 1934, which was a response to the social inequality and political turmoil that characterized the country at the time. The party initially faced severe repression from the Colombian government, but it gained momentum in the mid-20th century as part of the global wave of communism. The Colombian Communist Party has been involved in various political and social movements throughout its history, including the peasant farmers' movement and the trade union movement. It also played a significant role in the Colombian conflict, which lasted for more than five decades and resulted in millions of people displaced from their homes and significant loss of life. Although the communism movement in Colombia is not as strong as it once was, the legacy of the struggle for social justice and equality continues to shape the political landscape of the country.
